INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("106", "1", "2015-07-07 12:57:48", "2015-07-07 12:57:48", "<div class=\"post-content\">\r\n\r\nIts been a while since my last post and it seems I’m continually amazed by how things move rapidly on the NFV transformational front. Clearly our customers are heavily involved, but we’re also seeing some pretty aggressive moves from the vendor’s side of the equation.\r\n\r\nWe probably don’t share the same vision with all the vendors but it’s good to see that all the players in this market understand how very significant this transformation is and how it touches every aspect of the way operators architect and operate their networks.\r\n\r\nIn my previous posts I discussed the challenges our customers experience throughout their transformational journey to NFV: from daring to “Forget About The Hardware” to demanding “Real Openness” from their vendors.\r\n\r\nNow let’s move on to the business case. Contrary to popular belief, it’s not as trivial as you might imagine.\r\n\r\nIf you look at the promise of NFV, the business case looks pretty clear:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Transitioning to commodity HW means you should definitely see some cutback there from your previous expenditure on pricey, custom appliances.</li>\r\n	<li>Streamlining operational models means less dedicated teams for each service provided.</li>\r\n	<li>Sharing application resources means that the initial investment is diminished.</li>\r\n	<li>Distinctive pricing models (e.g. Pay as you grow) from your vendors allows you to shift to Opex by large, reducing the risk of launching new services</li>\r\n	<li>Efficient resource utilization means that you’re no longer creating purpose-built infrastructure for not-often recurring peak time operations (operators who construct entire networks just to support Mother’s Day texting or Black Friday shopping, are just a few of my favorite examples…)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSo why isn’t it as simple as that?\r\nI can think of three principal explanations:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>In reality, not all vendors are actually interested in things happening as fast as all that. I recently had an interesting talk with a someone from a major US carrier.  We spoke about vEPC deployment and he communicated a few interesting thoughts:\r\nIt seems that one of our competitors is pricing their vEPC higher than the actual legacy appliance. The rational they presented was that the virtual versions brings greater value to the carrier (e.g. simpler upgrade process, life cycle etc.), hence they should be priced higher…\r\nThe carrier obviously sees this as completely upside down reasoning and rightly so, but this is really just one example of the deliberate delays to the NFV transformation that are caused by the market.</li>\r\n	<li>When we’re only looking at the one or two applications that are readily available today, it becomes hard to see the bigger picture – the ultimate value down the road.\r\nNow, every transformation has overhead and as I stated, this particular transformation involves a major shift in the way operators architect and operate their network. Such a major shift always comes with a learning curve attached that clearly implicates upfront investments that operators must make in order to gain the long term ROI. But in the meantime, everybody’s evaluating the business case based on just one or two applications/services, so that the ROI just isn’t that sexy.\r\nOperators really have to keep this in mind and understand that what we’re actually doing is building an architecture that will serve multiple and diverse services in the long run.</li>\r\n	<li>The simple fact is that not all operators are created equal…\r\nObviously the business case changes dramatically for each and every operator network. It’s not that a dramatic change when you’re looking at the bigger picture, but it is pretty meaningful when you’re evaluating only a few services.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nSo, how do we build the right business case AND keep all of these variables in mind?\r\n\r\nFor me it all starts by sitting down with our customers, helping them believe and have faith in our vision, and and creating a solid agreement as to the goals of this transformation.\r\n\r\nAgain, this is not as straightforward as it sounds. This is a market that has seen its fair share of transformational promises and significant Opex/Capex reduction assurances. The market is wary (and rightly so), and it’s up to us to pass this hurdle and build the trust.\r\n\r\nBut once we do bridge the faith gap, it comes down to the in-depth discussions with the operations teams.  We really sit down with these teams to understand their day to day challenges and needs.\r\nI find this is probably the most meaningful and cost effective work we do with our customers.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a clear map of your customer’s operations and the goals are agreed on, then it’s time to address the transformation from a product perspective. Now you can start putting all the parts of the puzzle in place, working together with your customer to make sure that the business case works (and improves!) along every step of the journey.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://resources.alcatel-lucent.com/?cid=178476\">One such example is work we did with a customer on a simple DNS case – you can read it here</a>. I hope you’ll find it as helpful as we have.\r\n\r\nStay tuned – next week I’m going to jump into the fascinating and trendy topic of Professional Services in NFV.\r\n\r\nGuy\r\n\r\n</div>", "Transformation for NFV: Fourth lesson – Make The Business Case Work", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "opinion", "", "", "2015-08-12 23:56:46", "2015-08-12 18:56:46", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?page_id=106", "0", "page", "", "0");
