INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("357", "1", "2015-07-23 20:46:14", "0000-00-00 00:00:00", "Is the information and communication technology (ICT) sector a problem for the Earth’s climate? That was the idea examined at a recent symposium of the Royal Society in London. It is a disturbing idea to be sure, but it is based on the assumption that our current situation will not change - an assumption which is no longer valid, as many players are already actively engaged in bringing about change.\nAt Alcatel-Lucent we have made massive investments to address the issue of network power consumption. Our industrial research arm, Bell Labs, has provided a stark definition of the digital energy challenge facing us: more than 3.9 billion Internet users of some kind by 2017, producing an increase of 440% in data traffic and 720% for video. This explosion of digital network usage is quickly making the issue of the energy efficiency of ICT a priority.\n\nI would like to suggest that Alcatel-Lucent’s approach, going beyond our efforts to reduce our own carbon footprint, could serve as a model in terms of the complementary and comprehensive nature of its two components: a proactive strategy to improve the energy and carbon footprint of each new technology generation that we bring to market, combined with disruptive long-term R&amp;D programs.\n\nIn 2010 we launched the GreenTouch Consortium with industrial and academic partners to improve the energy efficiency of telecommunications networks by a factor of 1000 by 2020! On June 18th, in New York, GreenTouch will demonstrate that we have made our vision a reality, by publishing a portfolio of technologies capable of carrying the network traffic of 2020 but with power consumption below that of 2010.\n\nWith the future 5G communications standard, these major advances will enable the sustainable growth of mobile broadband. But digital technology can do more than this: I firmly believe that the ICT sector can contribute to solving the challenge of global climate change.\n\nThe role of digital technology goes well beyond the challenges of its own sector: through paperless offices, big data, information systems integration and industrial process optimization, digital technology puts itself at the heart of energy transition and the optimization of the ecological impact of all sectors of the economy. In its study SMARTer2020 1 , the Global e-Sustainability Initiative estimates the potential CO2 savings by other sectors (agriculture, transport, services, construction) to be seven times the emissions produced by the ICT sector—around nine Gigatons.\nICT’s contribution to addressing climate change can only accelerate with the Internet of Things, one of the essential paths to fully realizing the green potential of ICT at the global level.\n\nIn the face of reluctance from established habits and systems, an energy transition will only be realized and accelerated through such a deal  - a new policy framework which encompasses digital networks, enabling them to be modernized and deployed for universal access, and stimulating the convergence of digital and power networks to enable the development of intelligent, ecologically efficient buildings, cities, transport and industrial processes.\n\nCOP21, the United Nations Conference on Climate Change taking place in Paris later this year, is a crucial meeting for the creation of a digital New Deal for our climate. It must set a clear agenda for the progress we want to achieve and the levers for action which will enable it.\n\nThose of us investing in innovation need clarity on local targets for energy efficiency and carbon emission limits. These directly affect the riskiness and profitability of our solutions and their implementation by our customers. Carbon pricing plays a major role. In addition, access to fiscal incentives and financial instruments for green growth need to be provided, as do tendering procedures adapted to the energy efficiency targets which our technology solutions make possible. With these conditions, information and communication technologies will take their true place at the heart of COP 21: not among the problems, but at the top of the list of solutions.\n1 EDGAR data, Boston Consulting Group (BCG) analysis. A new edition, SMARTer 2030, is due to be published June 9th.", "Looking for another reason to embrace NFV? Go Green!", "", "draft", "open", "open", "", "", "", "", "2015-07-23 20:46:14", "2015-07-23 15:46:14", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=357", "0", "post", "", "0");
