INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("272", "1", "2015-07-22 16:59:19", "2015-07-22 16:59:19", "Get to NFV faster with an ecosystem of partners The CloudBand Ecosystem Program is an NFV community that was created to  encourage and facilitate the exchange, exploration and collaboration  of service providers, NFV platform partners and  virtual network function vendors to help accelerate NFV  development and implementation.\r\n\r\nThe program provides access to the <a href=\"/program/ecosystem-lab\">Cloud Innovation Center (CIC)</a> where there is open access  to the CloudBand NFV Platform and support resource and tools to  onboard applications from Alcatel‐Lucent or other 3rd party VNF’s.  It also provides a central portal for collaboration with other members and access to previously tested use cases and solution ideas to advance the deployment and business case for NFV.\r\n\r\nCreated in Oct 2013 and the first NFV Ecosystem launched, it now  has over 60 members: Service Providers, NFV Platform Partners  and Virtual Network Function Vendors. The program is by invitation only.\r\n\r\nAlcatel‐Lucent is an ecosystem member and our vIMS, vEPC, and vRAN utilize the CloudBand Innovation Center as a part of the NFV ecosystem. Nuage Networks is also a member of the ecosystem and Nuage Networks VSP is part of the CloudBand NFV Platform. Bell labs consulting services are also aligned with the ecosystem and are equipped to do business modeling and other consulting services triggered by ecosystem member requests.\r\n\r\n<strong>Our mission</strong>\r\nOperators cannot make the transition to virtualization alone. NFV is a complex and challenging process that brings together many new technologies and takes many minds working together to build this new architecture. Many smart and innovative vendors and operators are making significant contributions to specific parts of NFV, which prompted the need to surround us with partners that share our same philosophy.\r\n\r\nAlcatel‐Lucent believes in helping service providers get to NFV faster. This means:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Join forces to overcome complexity</li>\r\n	<li>Accelerate maturity of all NFV component</li>\r\n	<li>Validate VNF Lifecycle management approaches</li>\r\n	<li>Test the onboarding of many different VNF vendors</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>\nBenefits of joining the program</strong>\r\nOur program provides a hub, where application providers, platform partners and service \nproviders can share information and collaborate to create innovative NFV proof of concepts. We offer our members the opportunity to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Review use cases and proof points created with our community members</li>\r\n	<li>Connect to members and explore further mutual areas of interest</li>\r\n	<li>Participate in specific ecosystem events, round tables, trainings...</li>\r\n	<li>Get access to CloudBand ’s technical library</li>\r\n	<li>Bring us application partners and favorite use cases. We will provide access to a dedicated lab environment that includes the full CloudBand solution, as well as training and support to onboard apps onto CloudBand. (This lab is located at the Cloud Innovation Center (CIC) in Naperville, just outside Chicago).</li>\r\n	<li>Provide guidance and direction to make our Ecosystem offer the most value for your needs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/nfv-lab.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-269\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/nfv-lab.jpg\" alt=\"nfv-lab\" width=\"710\" height=\"325\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>On the way to certification</strong>\r\nThe CloudBand Ecosystem program is not a commercial program. It highlights collaboration but does not indicate endorsement of an application nor any agreement to resell. Any resale agreement that may exist would be created outside of the Ecosystem program.\r\n\r\nThe CloudBand Ecosystem program is primarily a collaboration program where we work to help the community understand NFV and how to operate in a cloud environment; it is not a certification program.\r\n\r\nParticipation in the program does not guarantee the quality of a VNF nor does it assess or assure the quality of deployment of the VNF into a service provider environment. We are building prototypes and use cases but are not certifying third‐party products or solutions. Moving forward, we will be able to provide more stringent test plans, pre‐ integration levels and deployment templates.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/60-ecosystem-members.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-271\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/60-ecosystem-members.png\" alt=\"60-ecosystem-members\" width=\"707\" height=\"352\" /></a>\r\n\r\nBy working together, the processes of specifying and integrating all the pieces can be faster, accelerating the reality of NFV in the cloud.\r\nValerie Noto\r\nDir CloudBand Ecosystem\r\n@valerienoto\r\n\r\n<a href=\"/contact\">Contact Us</a>", "Cloudband Ecosystem Program", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "7-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-07-22 16:59:19", "2015-07-22 16:59:19", "", "7", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/2015/07/22/7-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("273", "1", "2015-07-22 17:00:13", "2015-07-22 17:00:13", "Virtual firewall appliances play a critical role within the cloud infrastructure, mitigating security risks by implementing appropriate security controls for inter-virtual machine (VM) – or VM to physical and vice-versa – communication and providing the necessary isolation on an application, zone, domain or tenant basis.\r\n\r\nNetwork-based security services were traditionally implemented by strategically placing physical “middle-boxes” across data centers and assuming the underlying network fabric would remain relatively static. However, new cloud architectures contain virtualized infrastructure, making the end-points (VMs) and the network fabric dynamic and subject to rapid change due to some triggering event, such as a failed compute/storage resource causing an automated response from the orchestration layer. This has created issues with the traditional network security approach, ranging from inflexible physical topologies, to firewalls becoming chokepoints, to loss of VM traffic visibility within the host, to name a few.\r\n\r\nIn a virtualized environment, network service functions such as firewalls can be rapidly deployed when and where needed – independent of physical locations or boundaries – and stitched together with other virtual or physical network services (e.g., load-balancers) though the network functions virtualization concept of “service chaining”. This allows an agile, responsive and dynamic virtual environment to be created that scales based on events and configuration updates. It also ensures businesses can continue to monitor and enforce the same set of security controls and compliance requirements on the new virtual environment as they would with the traditional physical one.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Key Benefits:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"list-icon circle-no list-icon-color-#000 list-icon-check\">\r\n	<li>Basic building block for any virtual network fabric in cloud infrastructure for securing applications – both externally (using VPNs) and internally (zone/app firewall)</li>\r\n	<li>Elasticity/scalability based on demand conditions and operator defined KPIs</li>\r\n	<li>Self-healing of the firewall instances for high reliability and availability</li>\r\n	<li>Complete visibility and security of the virtual environment</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Solutions</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewalls are one of the basic building blocks within cloud infrastructure, required for securing access to/from the virtual environment as well as the applications running within the environment. Deployed within the virtual environment network fabric , they enable access controls to be used between virtual machines and other points in the virtual and physical environment. They play a significant role at various security layers – e.g. tenant isolation and security in a shared, multi-tenant environment (e.g. using VPNs); between applications within a given tenant (Zone firewall); between VMs within a given application (application firewall) and so on. They are essential in creating multi-tier virtual network functions/applications within a host environment.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Virtual Firewall Integration with CloudBand</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewall is deployed within CloudBand as an application appliance instance that can be used by other applications to create security controls between VMs within the application or across applications. There are two ways of using this virtual network function within CloudBand – it can be deployed as a standalone network function within a virtual network that is stitched together to form some higher level application/service or it can be deployed as a fully integrated network function within the framework of an application – e.g. a multi-tier web application. Independent of the deployment option, all applications are built by initially creating the necessary service templates called “recipes” using CloudBand’s cPaaS layer. The recipes essentially create the necessary service tiers for the application and manage the relationships between them, including all the scaling rules, healing rules, upgrades etc. The recipe is used to onboard the application onto CloudBand and make it available within the application/service catalogue for deployment.\r\n\r\nThe service provider/user can deploy the application by simply selecting the application from the application catalogue menu and providing any additional application-specific and/or operations-specific (business policy constraints) deployment parameters required. Upon deployment, the cPaaS manager monitors and controls the application activity as per the recipe definition/service template and the business policy constraints provided. CloudBand and cPaaS automatically provide all the underlying platform benefits to all deployed applications – such as elasticity, scalability, performance, reliability, availability, security and other common carrier-grade features – all without the need of deploying the applications on customized, proprietary hardware. Further, due to the cookie-cutter nature of the application template, deploying multiple instances requires little time or effort. The end result is the overall reduction in total cost of ownership for any deployed application – both in terms of Capex (since COTS hardware is employed) as well as Opex.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall on CloudBand use case: simple multi-tier application deployment architecture</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-278\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\" alt=\"use_case_FW_page_pic\" width=\"940\" height=\"475\" /></a>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall Cloudification Benefits: Operational Aspects</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"table-1\">\r\n<table width=\"100%\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th width=\"15%\">Attribute</th>\r\n<th>Conventional</th>\r\n<th>CloudBand</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Appliance</td>\r\n<td>Hardware appliance of software application on generic server (bare-metal) architected for peak capacity</td>\r\n<td>Virtualized software appliance on cloud infrastructure architected for current capacity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Deployment</td>\r\n<td>Site engineer investigates, deployment engineer installs, configures and provisions the system and monitors heath</td>\r\n<td>Management and orchestration system deploys new instance with standard configuration and automatically monitors health</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scale</td>\r\n<td>Add new cards/blades/servers into the system hardware and perform reconfiguration (re-architect with capacity planning)</td>\r\n<td>Orchestration system adds additional instances of the appliance and updates master-slave relationship configuration – can add/remove as many slaves as necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Upgrade</td>\r\n<td>Replace new upgraded blade with existing blade</td>\r\n<td>Upgrade a new virtual instance and simply switch traffic to it. Delete old instance</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Operations</td>\r\n<td>Hardware, operating system, application, alarms</td>\r\n<td>Operating system, hypervisor, application, alarms</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Multi-tenancy</td>\r\n<td>Service partitioning of hardware based systems can be quite cumbersome – or deploy multiple, parallel hardware/software systems</td>\r\n<td>Create a new service slice by deploying new application instance and service chain with other NFV components</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href==\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v3.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v2.pdf\">Powerpoint</a>", "VIRTUAL FIREWALL", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "virtual", "", "", "2015-10-27 12:04:24", "2015-10-27 07:04:24", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?page_id=273", "0", "page", "", "0");
