INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("309", "1", "2015-04-13 18:11:13", "2015-04-13 18:11:13", "<div class=\"post-content\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">One of the topics we tend to speak quite a bit about is the new TCO model enabled by our CloudBand Node, and for good reason: the CloudBand Node encourages a smarter, more efficient TCO, in line with the advantages and benefits NFV brings to the market as a whole.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Basically, it all comes down to the fundamental difference between Preventative Maintenance and Corrective Maintenance.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">To illustrate: When something happens to the really valuable, sentimental, irreplaceable things in your life, you try to fix them. You may even decide to spare no cost as long as they can be fixed. When your laptop or flat screen breaks down however, you’ll probably just go out and buy a new one. Right?</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So how do we translate this metaphor for our customers?</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">It’s really quite simple. We tell them to “Forget about the Hardware!”</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">We tell them to stop thinking about the underlying infrastructure. The NFV model makes sure that this is just commodity hardware that provides standard compute and storage. So, when it fails, more often than not, it’s outdated and will cost more to fix than to just pick up the phone and order a new one.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">(Do you know anyone who actually fixed their PC after they had it for more than two years?).</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">You can view our CloudBand-Node is one atomic unit. If the failure threshold is met you can simply define it as a failed Node and replace the whole unit instead of switching out each server at a time.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This simplicity and ease-of-use is due to the self-healing mechanism inherent in the CloudBand Management System which commissions out failed servers from the pool and moves the workload to other available resources.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Another dramatic characteristic this setup provides is the striking reduction in ongoing maintenance costs. In this model, operators don’t need to pay maintenance or even reduce it to minimum. Now just think about the extraordinary effect this brings to the overall TCO.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So yes, it’s not easy to say “forget about the hardware!” to your customers. In some cases it even sounds counterintuitive. But the NFV paradigm also means a stimulating educational journey – both for us, and for our customers.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">I hope these examples helped to get the concept budding and your wheels spinning – just think about how much sense it makes.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Guy</p>\r\n\r\n</div>", "Transformation for NFV: Thrid lesson – Forget about the hardware", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "transformation-for-nfv-thrid-lesson-forget-about-the-hardware", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:13:22", "2015-07-22 18:13:22", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=309", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("310", "1", "2015-07-22 18:11:13", "2015-07-22 18:11:13", "<div class=\"post-content\">\r\n<p class=\"western\">One of the topics we tend to speak quite a bit about is the new TCO model enabled by our CloudBand Node, and for good reason: the CloudBand Node encourages a smarter, more efficient TCO, in line with the advantages and benefits NFV brings to the market as a whole.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Basically, it all comes down to the fundamental difference between Preventative Maintenance and Corrective Maintenance.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">To illustrate: When something happens to the really valuable, sentimental, irreplaceable things in your life, you try to fix them. You may even decide to spare no cost as long as they can be fixed. When your laptop or flat screen breaks down however, you’ll probably just go out and buy a new one. Right?</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So how do we translate this metaphor for our customers?</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">It’s really quite simple. We tell them to “Forget about the Hardware!”</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">We tell them to stop thinking about the underlying infrastructure. The NFV model makes sure that this is just commodity hardware that provides standard compute and storage. So, when it fails, more often than not, it’s outdated and will cost more to fix than to just pick up the phone and order a new one.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">(Do you know anyone who actually fixed their PC after they had it for more than two years?).</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">You can view our CloudBand-Node is one atomic unit. If the failure threshold is met you can simply define it as a failed Node and replace the whole unit instead of switching out each server at a time.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This simplicity and ease-of-use is due to the self-healing mechanism inherent in the CloudBand Management System which commissions out failed servers from the pool and moves the workload to other available resources.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Another dramatic characteristic this setup provides is the striking reduction in ongoing maintenance costs. In this model, operators don’t need to pay maintenance or even reduce it to minimum. Now just think about the extraordinary effect this brings to the overall TCO.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So yes, it’s not easy to say “forget about the hardware!” to your customers. In some cases it even sounds counterintuitive. But the NFV paradigm also means a stimulating educational journey – both for us, and for our customers.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">I hope these examples helped to get the concept budding and your wheels spinning – just think about how much sense it makes.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Guy</p>\r\n\r\n</div>", "Transformation for NFV: Thrid lesson – Forget about the hardware", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "309-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:11:13", "2015-07-22 18:11:13", "", "309", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/2015/07/22/309-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("311", "1", "2015-04-02 18:12:18", "2015-04-02 18:12:18", "<div class=\"post-content\">\r\n<p class=\"western\"><i>Taking a break from my ongoing “Transformation for NFV” blog series in order to recount some of my conclusions from Mobile World Congress. Next week we’re back to the series with my insights on the role of Hardware in NFV.</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So MWC is over, and I’m back from five truly exciting and hectic days there. I’m pretty sure it was in Barcelona, but I actually only know it was there because that’s what it said on my plane ticket. It may as well have been anywhere at all as I only managed to see the Alcatel-Lucent booth and the route to the restrooms.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">I didn’t have time to check out the conference, look at the competition or try out cool new mobile communication gadgets let alone tour Barcelona, but I can tell you this:</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">NFV is EVERYWHERE. The stakes are high. Really high. But our bets are definitely paying off, and we are confident that NFV represents a true paradigm shift that is already changing EVERYTHING.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Four years ago when I first represented Alcatel-Lucent and CloudBand at MWC, we were talking about this crazy idea we liked to call “v-Telco”, and at that point in time I believe there were really only a few operators that actually got what we were talking about and also agreed with the value and benefits we proposed NFV would create.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This year the conversation was completely different.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">The discourse at MWC this year was utterly focused on concrete projects we are working on together with our customers, and on finalizing the timing for them. Clearly we will see deployments in 2015 with an NFV architecture. This indisputably shows the Market’s immense progress in both education and knowledge. Undeniably, there is still a lot that needs to be done, but the fact that operators are shifting from “CTO” types of research to actual deployment was great to witness.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"western\">From lock-in to lock-in</h2>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Another important thing to notice is that the conversation has definitely moved from “Box Differentiation” to “OpenStack Differentiation”</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">During one of the discussions I had, our customer raised an important point. He said that recently, all the vendors he talks with have gotten into the habit of extolling the virtues of their own OpenStack version, explaining why it’s better than others. Usually this can be mapped back to high levels of customization that create a distinctive OpenStack version.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So do you see what’s happening here?</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Until now vendor differentiation always focused on the box. “Our box is better for our application” was a common statement. Also, the statement “our box is stronger/faster with the latest technology” created a strong bundling between the app and the HW. This in turn promoted the silo approach with a “one vendor sells all” philosophy.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Now that “box differentiation” is becoming irrelevant, vendors are still striving for this all-inclusive “silo” approach, by leveraging OpenStack to the same cause.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">“Our OpenStack is stronger/better” and “Our OpenStack is certified for our application” are catch phrases we’re hearing more and more, and this was especially evident at MWC. However, this approach incontrovertibly places the market right back into the same vendor lock-in we know from the recent past. Moreover and far more troubling, is the fact that this clearly displaces a great deal of the value and benefits that NFV brings.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Now don’t get me wrong. I am of the opinion that vanilla OpenStack just isn’t enough, and CloudBand is also addressing OpenStack’s gaps for the needs of VNF’s. However, there are ways to extend OpenStack with plug-ins that will still maintain it as an open infrastructure, while providing our customers with the option to take advantage of these additions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"western\">Speaking the language of nfv</h2>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This year CloudBand held our second Ecosystem event at MWC, bringing all of our ecosystem members together for networking and to further the conversation on NFV readiness. This was also an opportunity for me to witness how our ecosystem members have progressed from generic plans for NFV compatibility to real action. Much of this progress may be attributed to the demands of our customers with regards to their NFV platform.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Still, I feel that there’s a sort of “language barrier” when we say “what does it take to be NFV ready” from the VNF perspective. The best example I can give is from a conversation I had with one of our European tier-1 customers who understands this domain well. He said that when a vendor tells him that he is “NFV ready” he gets down to the specifics and asks the really crucial question: “what EXACTLY have you changed in your app in order to be NFV ready?”</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This is the point! NFV requires changes in the applications. You need to provide the same services yet with a completely different set of assumptions. Different assumptions on how you handle Security and High Availability; Different assumptions on Upgrade Processes and on your expectations from the Infrastructure.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So it comes down to this: if you are an operator, the single most important question you should ask your NFV vendors is “What have you changed in the application?”</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"western\">NFV is everywhere</h2>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So yes, as I said in the beginning, NFV is everywhere and it’s changing everything. If you were at MWC like me you must have felt this great excitement and the vibe around NFV – it was palpable in the air!</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">You could feel it all around you and hear it from your partners and customers. I’m pretty sure there wasn’t a single vendor that sells to Telco without an NFV story – granted some of them have weak links to NFV, but hey, that market is here and everyone wants to jump on the wagon.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">From my personal perspective it’s really fantastic to see the how the market has evolved. But more than that – the hype and excitement of the past few years has been replaced with an even better sentiment – we are actually creating something that is a game changer in the most positive way possible – helping our customers solve the most meaningful challenges they face. I can’t wait to see what happens next!</p>\r\n\r\n</div>", "DONE WITH MWC – WHAT’S NEXT in the high stakes nfv game?", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "done-with-mwc-whats-next-in-the-high-stakes-nfv-game", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:12:36", "2015-07-22 18:12:36", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=311", "0", "post", "", "0");
