e ways to extend OpenStack with plug-ins that will still maintain it as an open infrastructure, while providing our customers with the option to take advantage of these additions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"western\">Speaking the language of nfv</h2>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This year CloudBand held our second Ecosystem event at MWC, bringing all of our ecosystem members together for networking and to further the conversation on NFV readiness. This was also an opportunity for me to witness how our ecosystem members have progressed from generic plans for NFV compatibility to real action. Much of this progress may be attributed to the demands of our customers with regards to their NFV platform.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Still, I feel that there’s a sort of “language barrier” when we say “what does it take to be NFV ready” from the VNF perspective. The best example I can give is from a conversation I had with one of our European tier-1 customers who understands this domain well. He said that when a vendor tells him that he is “NFV ready” he gets down to the specifics and asks the really crucial question: “what EXACTLY have you changed in your app in order to be NFV ready?”</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">This is the point! NFV requires changes in the applications. You need to provide the same services yet with a completely different set of assumptions. Different assumptions on how you handle Security and High Availability; Different assumptions on Upgrade Processes and on your expectations from the Infrastructure.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So it comes down to this: if you are an operator, the single most important question you should ask your NFV vendors is “What have you changed in the application?”</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"western\">NFV is everywhere</h2>\r\n<p class=\"western\">So yes, as I said in the beginning, NFV is everywhere and it’s changing everything. If you were at MWC like me you must have felt this great excitement and the vibe around NFV – it was palpable in the air!</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">You could feel it all around you and hear it from your partners and customers. I’m pretty sure there wasn’t a single vendor that sells to Telco without an NFV story – granted some of them have weak links to NFV, but hey, that market is here and everyone wants to jump on the wagon.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">From my personal perspective it’s really fantastic to see the how the market has evolved. But more than that – the hype and excitement of the past few years has been replaced with an even better sentiment – we are actually creating something that is a game changer in the most positive way possible – helping our customers solve the most meaningful challenges they face. I can’t wait to see what happens next!</p>\r\n\r\n</div>", "DONE WITH MWC – WHAT’S NEXT in the high stakes nfv game?", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "311-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:12:18", "2015-07-22 18:12:18", "", "311", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/2015/07/22/311-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("313", "1", "2015-03-02 18:15:18", "2015-03-02 18:15:18", "<div class=\"post-content\">\r\n\r\nNetwork Function Virtualization has affected everything in the Telco industry over the past several years – both on the Carriers side as well as the Vendors angle and to everything in between – and all this has happened with only the beginnings of commercial deployments starting to make themselves known.\r\n\r\nWe’re really just getting started, but look at the transformation we’ve already created!\r\n\r\nCarriers are shifting the way they operate their business, the way they manage their networks.\r\n\r\nVendors are completely changing the way they’re building applications and solutions.\r\n\r\nAnd even further- we see NFV opening the door to a new type of relationship between vendors and operators – a relationship built on understanding, on partnership and on mutual new markets, previously unaddressable.\r\n\r\nThis is a personal blog series, building on my own experience of creating what we all know today as NFV, with CloudBand and Alcatel-Lucent. I’ll discuss some of the areas that made us think differently and adjust the way we build a product, price it and discuss NFV strategy with our customers.\r\n\r\n<strong>SECOND LESSON – UNDERSTANDING THAT CHANGE IS INEVITABLE…</strong>\r\n\r\nNFV is a journey that creates inevitable change for our customers; Change that may disrupt the very way they operate their network.\r\n\r\nAs I discussed in my previous post, with any disruption comes a host of challenges which we as a vendor and a trusted partner need to fully understand before taking the first step towards a discussion with our customer on the topic.\r\n\r\nSo within any sizeable vendor environment, how do you handle these challenges and even more significantly – how do you communicate them to your customers?\r\n\r\nLet’s start with Openness.\r\n\r\nIt’s a pretty unambiguous goal, right? We want an open NFV Platform that any application can run on top of, while utilizing various forms of infrastructure.\r\n\r\nEasier said than done. And it has to begin with the basic understanding that you have to relinquish control. At least a little bit in the beginning, and more over time, as you learn that ‘Open’ is NOT synonymous with ‘Evil’.\r\n\r\nWhy is it so hard to relinquish control? Because today the vendors have it all, and that’s a pretty powerful thing.\r\n\r\nVendors today push the entire value chain, maybe with just a little bit of help from your favorite neighborly System Integrator. Not only that, the vendors hold themselves fully responsible for the entire process – from development, through testing and all the way to live commercial deployment. Now that’s a pretty neat model – simple and easy to understand. It also promotes and preserves vendor lock-in, leaving full control in the vendor’s hands for every step of the way.\r\n\r\nWell it IS a pretty neat model, but NFV is really all about openness. It’s a shift in power from the vendors to the operators, which puts the operators squarely back in the driver’s seat. NFV places the operators in a position where THEY have the power to switch things up, play with the components and be by far more flexible to their own market’s needs.\r\n\r\nIn my discussions with the various VNF vendors we work with, it may sometimes feel like I’m an NFV therapist. And as in any good therapy, the first step is to accept that you have a problem. Once a vendor recognizes that they have a problem, only then can we start talking about openness.\r\n\r\nIn these ‘therapy’ sessions I usually ask a few really simple questions that help determine the vendors’ true level of openness:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Did you change your applications (VNFs) to support NFV?</li>\r\n	<li>Have you worked with 3rd parties?</li>\r\n	<li>Can you work on different types of Hardware?</li>\r\n	<li>Do you leverage the community?</li>\r\n	<li>Have you clearly defined Roles and Responsibilities?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet’s break them down one by one, OK?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Did you change your applications (VNFs) to support NFV?\r\n</strong>Well obviously, the answer here will always be a resounding ‘YES’. But then you have to dive into the specifics and find out what exactly was changed. And the answer here has to be more than ‘well, we moved to KVM hypervisors’.An application must transform when it runs on 3rd party infrastructure. The vendor should assume that the infrastructure provides ONLY compute, storage and networking – nothing more! Yes – It’s up to the application to handle service continuity! And it has to support Southbound APIs without any dependencies on the infrastructure. (And if you hear “Well, we’re only certified on HW ‘X’” then something is definitely wrong….”)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Have you worked with 3rd parties?</strong>You’ll be surprised how many opportunities we have to work with other vendors, and most of the operators are really keen to see their vendors speak with each other and are even happier to broker these discussions.It’s important to take advantage of this. It’s always easier to run and end-to-end solution based on your own portfolio, but once you start to work with 3rd parties, new questions will pop-up and additional requirements will push you to create a truly open platform.Alcatel-Lucent’s CloudBand Ecosystem was created with that very intention in mind – to create a truly open, interoperable NFV offering based on the CloudBand NFV platform with seamlessly on-boarded VNF’s from a multitude of vendors. 60 Ecosystem members later (and going strong), this goal is proving itself every day at our field trials and deployments worldwide.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Can you work on different types of Hardware?</strong>And no, I don’t mean ATCA or costume HW. I mean plain old, simple, x86 pizza boxes. Remember – one of our main goals here is to lower costs and leverage Moore’s law. I’m going to be talking a lot about Hardware in one of my upcoming posts so stay tuned for that; but in the meantime, when you speak with application vendors you need to make sure they don’t expect the HW to provide any more than Compute, Storage and Networking. To maintain openness, applications should be agnostic to the Operators’ HW choices.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Do you leverage the community?</strong>The level of innovation in NFV is huge, and vendors are constantly on the lookout for innovation and if it comes from within, so much the better. One of the best ways to foster innovation is through the power of the community. Just look at OpenStack as an example! OpenStack’s growth and maturation was without a question a tremendous accelerant for the adoption of NFV, providing a much needed jump start for the end-to-end story. Granted, OpenStack is perhaps an extreme example, but there are countless open tools and capabilities developed by the community that any NFV platform or VNF vendor could (and should!) leverage.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Have you clearly defined Roles and Responsibilities?</strong>This is without doubt the era of “R&amp;R” and any NFV vendor should be thinking very hard about the transformation required when implementing their offering. I’ll be elaborating on Roles and Responsibilities in another post, but in a nutshell, we’re moving from a solution that is implemented by one vendor to a combination of capabilities between a variety of vendors. You can’t deploy it without understanding clearly who is responsible for what:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>What expectations should the VNF have from the NFV Platform?</li>\r\n	<li>What should the NFV platform assume the VNF can manage?</li>\r\n	<li>Who handles the EMS and VNFM?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll of these items need clarification and definition from any vendors that claim to be truly open.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOpenness is vital for NFV – there is no doubt about it, and while the benefits of openness to the operators (and vendors!) are great, openness also embodies change that must be considered and embraced.\r\n\r\nThe above are some fundamental discussion points to bring up when talking about openness with your customers, partners and vendors – but they are also crucial design guidelines for anyone in this business. Let’s bring openness one step closer to becoming a reality for NFV by making sure we’re asking ourselves and our partners the right questions.\r\n\r\nNext time (as promised): A different way to look at Hardware See you soon,\r\nGuy\r\n\r\n</div>", "Transformation for NFV: Second Lesson – Understanding That Change Is Inevitable", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "transformation-for-nfv-second-lesson-understanding-that-change-is-inevitable", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:15:29", "2015-07-22 18:15:29", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=313", "0", "post", "", "0");
