r problems are more on the technical side, i.e. how our customers actually operate their networks.\r\n\r\nHowever, with NFV it’s much more than that, and requires deep though and real transformational processes. Why? Because NFV changes everything. NFV has touch points at almost every part of a carrier’s business and network. It impacts every single process.\r\n\r\nPerhaps I can more easily describe these impact points by relating some genuine feedback I received from several of our customers regarding the claims made by NFV advocates:\r\n\r\n<strong>NFV Claim #1: “NFV means to move from Specialist dedicated HW to high volume commercial HW”\r\n</strong>Customer reaction: “For years on end vendors have been claiming that your solutions will run best only on specialized dedicated HW. Now you’re saying that HW doesn’t really matter?”\r\n<strong>NFV Claim #2: “NFV enables you to avoid vendor lock-in and work in an open environment…”\r\n</strong>Customer reaction: “how do I know who to call now? Today I only have a single point of contact. How will it work in a multi-vendor environment?”\r\n<strong>NFV Claim #3: “OpenSource creates more opportunities and greater flexibility for NFV”\r\n</strong>Customer reaction: “My organization can’t influence OpenSource activities. We don’t know how to deal with support and update issues. Who’s responsible when I have a network outage or find a software bug?\r\n<strong>NFV Claim #4: “The Carrier Grade Service expectation is reachable through SW”\r\n</strong>Customer reaction: “you’ve changed the entire philosophy that you’ve been preaching for the past 20 years….”\r\n\r\nAnd so on… the examples above are only a few of the immense challenges and some misconceptions our customers face on the path to NFV transformation.\r\n\r\nOur experience over the past few years has unequivocally shown us that when we approach a customer with an NFV focused discussion we have to keep in mind the magnitude of change they will have to go through, however we also have to remember that much of this change is not specifically technology related but is on a much more basic level – the level of the day to day operational necessities of running a network. Our customers have years of best-practice operations within their network which will virtually all change throughout this technological journey. With our customers it’s our job to make sure that this journey does not risk the end customers service experience and will be a better one for everyone involved if they travel it with us alongside.\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll elaborate a bit more about this journey, what the journey means to an NFV vendor and how we focus on operational readiness.\r\n\r\nGuy", "Transformation for NFV: First lesson – Understanding the customer’s challenges…", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "315-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:17:04", "2015-07-22 18:17:04", "", "315", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/2015/07/22/315-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("318", "1", "2014-11-19 18:18:05", "2014-11-19 18:18:05", "<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Andreas-CHCo-150x150.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-320\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Andreas-CHCo-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Andreas-CHCo-150x150\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>The SDN &amp; OpenFlow World Congress was the venue where the original NFV whitepaper was published in 2012. Now, in Düsseldorf, Germany, we could see how NFV and SDN had flourished from the seed placed two years ago. Stretched to full capacity, the event attracted 1300 attendees, almost twice as many as last year. But it was not only the number of attendees but also the quality of the audience. Unlike broader events, such as the Mobile World Congress, the audience of this event was specialists from service providers, vendors, analysts, and research institutions with a focus on NFV and SDN making the event the premier venue for anybody wishing to learn about the state of the industry. Many of the CloudBand ecosystem members attended the event and had their booths in the exhibition hall or showed their solutions in the ETSI PoC Zone.\r\n\r\nDespite missing from the name of the event, observers such as Jerry Caron of Current Analysis voiced the impression that NFV was really the primary topic. Be that as it may, many attendees agreed that SDN is an integral element of NFV providing the programmability for the network desperately needed for any NFV installation. As Dor Skuler pointed out, anything is feasible with enough programmers and enough pizza but trying to do more complex use cases without a programmable SDN network is not efficient.\r\n\r\nThe combination of SDN and NFV was also at the center of the discussions with customers and analysts at the Alcatel-Lucent stand. One of the live demonstrations showed how service providers can quickly deploy new revenue generating services and make these services selectively available to different subscribers. The demonstration illustrated the power of the CloudBand NFV platform along with a Nuage Networks SDN solution to build a value added service infrastructure with virtual network functions and virtual networks within minutes. But the demonstration was not only about deployment but also about integration into the OSS and BSS layers. What good is a deployment time for a VNF of a few minutes when it takes weeks to configure the necessary networks and many months to integrate a new virtual network function into the fulfillment and assurance procedures? Thanks to the CloudBand and Nuage Networks open REST APIs, such processes can be quickly automated. Subscribers can select services from a self-service portal and the APIs immediately activate the services by changing the subscribers’ service chains. Subscribers no longer have to wait until the end of the month before they can take advantage of the selected services, an improvement that creates a much more immediate customer experience.\r\n\r\nMany discussions centered around the concept of service chaining. What are the implementation options? How scalable is service chaining in an environment with millions of subscribers? One customer wondered about the impact of licensing on NFV. What happens when only a limited number of licenses is available for a virtual network function? How are the licenses distributed across the VNF deployments in different locations without wasting some of them? Is there an impact on scaling and service routing?\r\n\r\nAnother topic of questions and discussions was TOSCA – Topology and Orchestration Specification for Cloud Applications. To achieve a truly horizontal NFV platform, a shared pool of resources without vendor-specific silos, this platform needs to be able to support NFV applications from any vendor; and to manage and orchestrate these applications, a standardized modeling language would be highly beneficial. With that, VNF vendors could model their applications once and run them on the NFV platforms of any service provider. The ETSI NFV ISG considers TOSCA as a prime candidate for its concept of NFV descriptor. TOSCA allows VNF vendors and service providers to describe the virtual machines and networks needed to deploy the VNF as well as rules for scaling and other lifecycle operations.\r\n\r\nIf one thing was obvious at the event, it was that NFV is here to stay and will fundamentally change the telecommunications industry. Vendors and service providers have started to transform themselves making cloud and NFV central to their infrastructures with new roles and responsibilities as well as new business models. See you next time at SDN &amp; OpenFlow", "NFV is hot at SDN & OpenFlow World Congress", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "nfv-is-hot-at-sdn-openflow-world-congress", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:18:46", "2015-07-22 18:18:46", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=318", "0", "post", "", "0");
