INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("326", "1", "2015-07-22 18:22:00", "2015-07-22 18:22:00", "<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/ido_miran.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-325\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/ido_miran.jpg\" alt=\"ido_miran\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><strong>CloudBand Research and Development</strong>\r\nIn the past couple of years we’ve seen the NFV vision rapidly evolve from the operators’ “I have a dream”, to the vendors’ “yes we can”. And now is the time to finally “just do it”. But are we really ready for actually “doing it”?\r\n\r\nA lot has been said around the disruption that NFV brings to “the way operators operate”. Some may even claim that NFV will rise or fall on the operators’ ability to successfully manage this change. But hey, Rome wasn’t built in a day and even after 2,000 years it is still being developed (although I must admit that whenever I’m in Rome I hardly ever see any construction sites…). The way operators operate is something that can, and most likely will, evolve over a long period of time. So as I see it, no excuses there: operators can start deploying “lean” NFV right away! Lean, in terms of VNF complexity and scale. The most important thing is to make that crucial (and may I add, historic?) step: out of the lab, and into the real world.\r\n\r\nIt seems that while operators are challenging vendors with the current state of readiness of their NFV platforms &amp; VNFs for full-scale production, operators are in turn challenged with their current ability to embrace and successfully apply the operational transformation that the NFV paradigm shift brings about. Not to mention the state of readiness of the current mesh (was that an ‘h’ or an ‘s’? hmm…) of legacy OSS deployments to handle all this virtualized telco disruption.\r\n\r\n<strong>So, are the operators operationally ready for this?</strong>\r\nMy take is that starting lean will serve the operational aspects of NFV just as it would serve the technological ones. Waiting for the full blown end-to-end NFV operational processes and systems to settle, and building a detailed 5-year plan for restructuring the operator’s tens of thousands of employees around new teams with new areas of expertise to provide a 100% match with the needs of the NFV era is not really needed for getting started.\r\n\r\n<strong>And what about the vendors?</strong>\r\nIn order to make it into the operator’s production environment, both the NFV platform and on-boarded VNFs must ensure “carrier grade” capabilities in terms of resiliency, performance, operability (yes, the good old FCAPS…), supportability and of course security.\r\n\r\nWhen I come to think of it, as CloudBand Ecosystem brings together partners from both the operators and the vendors arenas, it would be extremely interesting to hear your take on this… are the operational challenges surmountable in the short term? What does “carrier grade” really mean in NFV? And what are the current obstacles on the way to getting NFV out there, “coming soon to a network near you”?", "Lean #NFV – Coming Soon To A Network Near You", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "324-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:22:00", "2015-07-22 18:22:00", "", "324", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/2015/07/22/324-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
