INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("341", "1", "2014-12-04 18:29:49", "2014-12-04 18:29:49", "It’s been a really hectic few months as we come to the end of the 2013 Industry events. It’s amazing that only a year ago, the term NFV did not exist and now we see it center stage for many existing and new events.\r\n\r\nBBWF was a good example – they focused one of their 5 tracks on Virtualization and Cloud. The room was full to capacity with people standing around the edges to hear the latest news. I managed to sit in on a few talks and one was from Don Clark who is the Chair of the Network Operator Council  for the ETSI NFV group and also Head of Network Evolution Innovation at BT. Don said ‘NFV is not about creating standards – we use what standards exist’. And how right he is. We already have standards, maybe not the ones we are used to in the past such as 3GPP, but new open source ones like Open Stack. And we can write the additional logic required to make it work for NFV.\r\n\r\nDon also stressed the need for common/shared hardware and we must have an open ecosystem. Of course I was happy to hear that and he also acknowledged Alcatel-Lucent for the work we are doing here. Our CloudBand ecosystem is gaining strong momentum and as you can see, we now have 27 partners with 14 more coming. We’re learning a lot from each other and that’s what it’s all about.\r\n\r\nDor Skuler, our President of the CloudBand Business group, talked about the progress being made in the proof of concepts with service providers. Several of them started with simpler appliances like DNS and AAA, and then moved to the more complex applications like IMS. But what has taken us by surprise is the speed at which even data plane applications, like EPC, have sprung up. But what’s clear is that service providers are not so much asking virtualization questions but now cloud questions – how do I deploy, how do I scale, who is responsible for what, how do I recover from a failure, how do I do route call analysis etc.\r\n\r\nBut the biggest question of all was – how do I get started. The response from Dor was ‘take baby steps’. Pick a low risk project like DNS, start small and prove it in in your own organization and work out all the new operational practices. And do this while you continue with proof of concepts on the more complex virtualized applications.\r\n\r\nWhat’s important for us all is to shift to a cloud mindset. In ALU, CloudBand is that catalyst for change in our own company and we’re glad we have the CloudBand ecosystem so our partners can benefit also in the critical next stages of NFV. And thanks for the award BBWF, we were happy to walk away from the event with a Highly Commended for CloudBand – the Platform for NFV in the category of Best Broadband Cloud Award.", "NFV takes center stage at Industry events with some strong messages.", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "nfv-takes-center-stage-at-industry-events-with-some-strong-messages", "", "", "2015-07-22 18:30:04", "2015-07-22 18:30:04", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=341", "0", "post", "", "0");
