INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("796", "5", "2015-09-16 22:56:19", "2015-09-16 17:56:19", "So how do Professional Services fit into the NFV journey?\r\n\r\nThis is a pretty complex issue that’s hard to cover in one post, but I do want to highlight a few key points and lay out what I believe is the correct approach.\r\n\r\nProfessional Services are by nature a low-entry-threshold offering that historically has the potential of major income for vendors.\r\n\r\nTraditionally, It’s almost impossible to predict the real cost of required professional services on a telecommunications project that can span 3 years or more – and this unpredictable cost is a source of concern for service providers.\r\n\r\nIn addition, Professional Services are not a product in and of itself, but rather an ongoing process of installation, integration, commissioning, interoperability and other tailored items.\r\n\r\nOnce you start the project there are always new items in the process that must be added. At this point, it’s quite impractical to stop or revert the activity and you find yourself invariably coughing up the extra resources.\r\n\r\nAnd even more infuriating for the customers, professional services also contribute to creating vendor lock-in as  more and more customization is made  with time. As your project becomes more tailored to your network, to your OSS and to other crucial system elements it becomes troublesome and tricky to replace. Not only that, it creates a vicious cycle of endless maintenance and support.\r\n\r\nAnd so it goes… there are additional reasons, but these alone bring huge incentive to vendors to increase their services offering. And unfortunately it gets even more complex with a variety of strategies on “how-to-sell” services: from ‘start small and increase later’ tosophisticated rationalizations about the complexity of the project and the need of a strong vendor to support it. You’ve probably heard them all…\r\n\r\nBut, and it’s a big one here – NFV (as I’ve already mentioned several times) changes everything. And Professional Services aren’t exempt from this change. We’ve talked previously about how NFV means big OPEX savings right? Well Professional Services can be a huge chunk of that OPEX, and what’s more it’s also perfectly aligned with the NFV transformation and the shift to software.\r\n\r\nAnd yet – how do you leverage this transformation and deal with services appropriately?\r\n\r\nWell the way I see it, a lot of it should simply disappear, and the remainder needs to adjust to the new software focused world.\r\n\r\nAs a customer you should expect to have a solution that is almost fully automated in installation and life cycle management, allowing Professional Services to transform into the more advanced stuff.\r\n\r\nAdvanced automation allows you to focus on the end-to-end solution and not on the nitty-gritty of the product itself. After you’ve gained the advantages of automation, you’re left with customized Professional Services offerings, such as interoperability between vendors, integration between different product layers (E.g. NFVI ,MANO, VNF) and integration with the OSS.\r\n\r\nNFV doesn’t mean the end of Professional Services. It means a shift to accommodate new industry standards and most importantly to truly gain from and leverage the immense benefits NFV can bring if utilized correctly.\r\n\r\nSo… ask your vendors what does their Professional Services portfolio offer with their NFV deployment. If you’re getting the same answers you’re used to getting, stop and reassess. It’s easy to forget about Professional Services when you’re thinking about the massive operational and architectural transformation you’re undergoing. Nevertheless, with this transformation come huge OPEX benefits – no reason not to take full advantage of them.\r\n\r\nNext time – Putting the OSS in its place\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "Transformation for NFV: Fifth lesson – Professional Services in NFV - Where Do They Fit In?", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "transformation-for-nfv-fifth-lesson-professional-services-in-nfv-where-do-they-fit-in", "", "", "2015-09-16 22:58:34", "2015-09-16 17:58:34", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=796", "0", "post", "", "0");
