INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("801", "5", "2015-09-16 22:59:54", "2015-09-16 17:59:54", "In this blog I’ve been reviewing the NFV journey I’ve gone through over the past few years. In each post I try to highlight a different concept or issue that comes up in our discussions with customers (although not in order of importance obviously).\r\n\r\nAs you’ve probably noticed, there are still a lot of questions to answer and a general lack of knowledge around NFV and I do hope this blog helps to sort it out a bit.\r\n\r\nThis time lets talk a bit about OSS. Another big elephant in the room.\r\n\r\nHere are some of the statements we hear from customers:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>NFV will require re-architecting our OSS</li>\r\n	<li>NFV savings are meaningless, I can save much more by introducing automation within my OSS</li>\r\n	<li>NFV will require a real-time OSS structure</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLet’s deal with these points one by one.\r\n\r\n<strong>Does NFV by definition require “re-architecting” your OSS?</strong>\r\n\r\nHold your horses… If that were true it would be many years before we would see any meaningful deployments (and we already know that’s not the case).\r\n\r\nThe concept that we at Alcatel-Lucent are talking about today (and which I see from other vendors as well), is to assume that the OSS doesn’t change.\r\n\r\nOperators typically invest billions of dollars to build their OSS and they usually have fairly complex and customized ones. Changes to these systems are complicated and costly to say the least.\r\n\r\nSo what should vendors do to make the NFV transformation easier with regards to the OSS? First, Vendors must make sure that they support the standard interfaces to any OSS. Second, the focus should be on greenfields or expansions. Trying to replace existing services which are already hooked to the OSS is infinitely more complex. Ultimately, you really need to stay smart and pragmatic – find ways to get in where small changes are needed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Does OSS automation positively affect OPEX more than NFV? </strong>\r\n\r\nThis is a classic claim by OSS vendors which is fairly accurate. Automation in OSS can obviously save a lot. However, let’s decouple the conversation. There’s a clear need to streamline and automate the OSS. This continuous effort by vendors and operators is challenging due to the high customization levels the OSS has by nature within the Operator’s network.\r\n\r\nBut NFV runs in a different domain. It about automation but more importantly it’s about streamlining operational processes that transform the way operators manage their network. Yes, automation is a big part of it but it’s definitely not the most crucial part. What’s important to note is that automation within the OSS isn’t really NFV related at all, but rather just an additional step taken to simplify operations and reduce OPEX.\r\n\r\n<strong>Does NFV open the way for “real-time OSS? </strong>\r\n\r\nI have to say that I think it does. Once you enable network automation, the ability to identify issues, react and predict, increases significantly. Inevitably, vendors should take advantage of this increased capability and offer a more advanced real-time OSS system. Network Service Orchestration is an example, and we’ll discuss it in detail in a future post. For now, however, NSO means the ability to offer new services and address the entire instantiation from the second the end-user requests it and until the last billing configuration can be done in real-time (after NFV has been implemented in the network).\r\n\r\nOther examples can be found in capacity planning and root cause analysis where real-time knowledge on network and resources consumption as well as failure can trigger real-time events in the OSS layer. Such events can ensure on-going service delivery.\r\n\r\nSo, no need to be be anxious. We not about to change your OSS - we don’t really have to. When you make a technological project so complex that it pushes away innovation and disruption, you’re defeating the purpose. Let’s concentrate on keeping NFV simple, and ensuring connectivity to existing systems, and deal with OSS on a separate track.\r\n\r\nNext up, let’s take a step back in time – where do you start in NFV?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "Transformation for NFV: Sixth lesson – Putting the OSS in its Place", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "putting-the-oss-in-its-place", "", "", "2015-10-27 17:55:44", "2015-10-27 12:55:44", "", "0", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/?p=801", "0", "post", "", "0");
