INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("962", "1", "2015-10-27 11:55:18", "2015-10-27 06:55:18", "In this use case, Alcatel-Lucent and CloudBand™ Ecosystem program member F5 Networks have worked\r\ntogether to demonstrate Virtual Network Function (VNF) deployment of F5 BIG-IP Local Traffic Manager\r\n(LTM) virtual appliance with Domain Name Server (DNS) infrastructure on top of the CloudBand platform.\r\n\r\n<h2>Challenge</h2>\r\nIn the past, service providers installed multiple servers to serve all users (for example, DNS,DHCP). However, the growth of users’ traffic as well as the need for high availability requires adding more servers and a high throughput load balancer for traffic distribution. Therefore, the maintenance of the solution became a complex task: adding an additional DNS server required buying the hardware, and then installing, configuring and adding it to the load balancer configuration during a maintenance window. The use of physical servers resulted in high capital expenditures (CAPEX) and operating expenses (OPEX), which  in turn required a different operating model\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/PR1509013959EN_Cloudband_ecosystem_Usecase1.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>", "VNF deployment of Domain Name Servers  based on F5 application delivery controller", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "844-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 11:55:18", "2015-10-27 06:55:18", "", "844", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/844-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("963", "1", "2015-10-27 11:59:27", "2015-10-27 06:59:27", "Virtual firewall appliances play a critical role within the cloud infrastructure, mitigating security risks by implementing appropriate security controls for inter-virtual machine (VM) – or VM to physical and vice-versa – communication and providing the necessary isolation on an application, zone, domain or tenant basis.\r\n\r\nNetwork-based security services were traditionally implemented by strategically placing physical “middle-boxes” across data centers and assuming the underlying network fabric would remain relatively static. However, new cloud architectures contain virtualized infrastructure, making the end-points (VMs) and the network fabric dynamic and subject to rapid change due to some triggering event, such as a failed compute/storage resource causing an automated response from the orchestration layer. This has created issues with the traditional network security approach, ranging from inflexible physical topologies, to firewalls becoming chokepoints, to loss of VM traffic visibility within the host, to name a few.\r\n\r\nIn a virtualized environment, network service functions such as firewalls can be rapidly deployed when and where needed – independent of physical locations or boundaries – and stitched together with other virtual or physical network services (e.g., load-balancers) though the network functions virtualization concept of “service chaining”. This allows an agile, responsive and dynamic virtual environment to be created that scales based on events and configuration updates. It also ensures businesses can continue to monitor and enforce the same set of security controls and compliance requirements on the new virtual environment as they would with the traditional physical one.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Key Benefits:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"list-icon circle-no list-icon-color-#000 list-icon-check\">\r\n	<li>Basic building block for any virtual network fabric in cloud infrastructure for securing applications – both externally (using VPNs) and internally (zone/app firewall)</li>\r\n	<li>Elasticity/scalability based on demand conditions and operator defined KPIs</li>\r\n	<li>Self-healing of the firewall instances for high reliability and availability</li>\r\n	<li>Complete visibility and security of the virtual environment</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Solutions</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewalls are one of the basic building blocks within cloud infrastructure, required for securing access to/from the virtual environment as well as the applications running within the environment. Deployed within the virtual environment network fabric , they enable access controls to be used between virtual machines and other points in the virtual and physical environment. They play a significant role at various security layers – e.g. tenant isolation and security in a shared, multi-tenant environment (e.g. using VPNs); between applications within a given tenant (Zone firewall); between VMs within a given application (application firewall) and so on. They are essential in creating multi-tier virtual network functions/applications within a host environment.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Virtual Firewall Integration with CloudBand</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewall is deployed within CloudBand as an application appliance instance that can be used by other applications to create security controls between VMs within the application or across applications. There are two ways of using this virtual network function within CloudBand – it can be deployed as a standalone network function within a virtual network that is stitched together to form some higher level application/service or it can be deployed as a fully integrated network function within the framework of an application – e.g. a multi-tier web application. Independent of the deployment option, all applications are built by initially creating the necessary service templates called “recipes” using CloudBand’s cPaaS layer. The recipes essentially create the necessary service tiers for the application and manage the relationships between them, including all the scaling rules, healing rules, upgrades etc. The recipe is used to onboard the application onto CloudBand and make it available within the application/service catalogue for deployment.\r\n\r\nThe service provider/user can deploy the application by simply selecting the application from the application catalogue menu and providing any additional application-specific and/or operations-specific (business policy constraints) deployment parameters required. Upon deployment, the cPaaS manager monitors and controls the application activity as per the recipe definition/service template and the business policy constraints provided. CloudBand and cPaaS automatically provide all the underlying platform benefits to all deployed applications – such as elasticity, scalability, performance, reliability, availability, security and other common carrier-grade features – all without the need of deploying the applications on customized, proprietary hardware. Further, due to the cookie-cutter nature of the application template, deploying multiple instances requires little time or effort. The end result is the overall reduction in total cost of ownership for any deployed application – both in terms of Capex (since COTS hardware is employed) as well as Opex.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall on CloudBand use case: simple multi-tier application deployment architecture</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-278\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\" alt=\"use_case_FW_page_pic\" width=\"940\" height=\"475\" /></a>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall Cloudification Benefits: Operational Aspects</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"table-1\">\r\n<table width=\"100%\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th width=\"15%\">Attribute</th>\r\n<th>Conventional</th>\r\n<th>CloudBand</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Appliance</td>\r\n<td>Hardware appliance of software application on generic server (bare-metal) architected for peak capacity</td>\r\n<td>Virtualized software appliance on cloud infrastructure architected for current capacity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Deployment</td>\r\n<td>Site engineer investigates, deployment engineer installs, configures and provisions the system and monitors heath</td>\r\n<td>Management and orchestration system deploys new instance with standard configuration and automatically monitors health</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scale</td>\r\n<td>Add new cards/blades/servers into the system hardware and perform reconfiguration (re-architect with capacity planning)</td>\r\n<td>Orchestration system adds additional instances of the appliance and updates master-slave relationship configuration – can add/remove as many slaves as necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Upgrade</td>\r\n<td>Replace new upgraded blade with existing blade</td>\r\n<td>Upgrade a new virtual instance and simply switch traffic to it. Delete old instance</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Operations</td>\r\n<td>Hardware, operating system, application, alarms</td>\r\n<td>Operating system, hypervisor, application, alarms</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Multi-tenancy</td>\r\n<td>Service partitioning of hardware based systems can be quite cumbersome – or deploy multiple, parallel hardware/software systems</td>\r\n<td>Create a new service slice by deploying new application instance and service chain with other NFV components</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v3.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v2.pdf\">Powerpoint</a>", "VIRTUAL FIREWALL", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "273-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 11:59:27", "2015-10-27 06:59:27", "", "273", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/273-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("964", "1", "2015-10-27 12:00:40", "2015-10-27 07:00:40", "<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Value to the ecosystem</h2>\r\n</div>\r\nA session border controller (SBC) is a network element used to support voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP), multimedia, next-generation presence-based applications for wireline, 3G and voice over LTE, IMS and pre-IMS networks.\r\n\r\nSBCs play an important role at the network edge by providing signaling and media security, service level agreement assurance and regulatory compliance capabilities. SBC features for multimedia applications such as voice, fax and video include: far- and near-end Network Address Translation traversal/firewall; secure Real-time Transport Protocol; IPv4/IPv6 networking; Call Admission Control; session routing; overload protection; transcoding; and quality of service and regulatory compliance.\r\n\r\nSBCs can be located at smaller points of presence – supporting as few as 5000 subscribers – or in larger central offices or data centers supporting millions of subscribers. It is a critical component for managing Internet traffic to help safeguard the multimedia communications that are integral to our daily lives as the number of IP devices continues to grow.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Key Benefits:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"list-icon circle-no list-icon-color-#000 list-icon-check\">\r\n	<li>SBC signaling functions are very compute intensive and will greatly benefit from implementation on commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) cloud infrastructure</li>\r\n	<li>An important SBC function is to protect against denial of service and distributed denial of services attacks – using low-cost hardware to manage unexpected surges while maintaining support for non-attack traffic is crucial.</li>\r\n	<li>Just-in-time deployment flexibility</li>\r\n	<li>Almost infinite elasticity and scalability</li>\r\n	<li>Support for new services, such as “SBC as a service”</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Solutions</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nThe SBC is well suited to cloud deployment, where it can be fully virtualized and deployed on a cloud Network Function Virtualization platform such as CloudBand. There it can take full advantage of the underlying infrastructure to obtain the necessary distributed or local deployment flexibility, elasticity, reliability and high availability. These are all critical for carrier-grade operations; however cloud deployment eliminates the need for closed, customized or proprietary hardware. The common, distributed infrastructure – with centralized management and orchestration – can be shared between many similar carrier-specific applications to achieve economies of scale.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Cloud-based Session Border Controller:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nThe virtualized SBC is deployed onto the CloudBand platform using the carrier platform as a service (cPaaS) layer by creating a set of recipes (like a template or a cookie cutter) that deploy the necessary service tiers for the application and manage the relationship between these services. In addition, the recipe provides full application lifecycle management, including scaling (based on defined key performance indicators), self-healing and upgrading. This essentially creates a simple, one-touch, automated, end-to-end application deployment that also accommodates any operator-specific constraints.\r\n\r\nDue to the cookie-cutter nature of the application template, deploying multiple instances requires little time or effort. Further, the underlying infrastructure, in conjunction with the management and orchestration system, provides the necessary reliability, availability and security for the application to meet the strict carrier-grade requirements, all on COTS hardware.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>SBC on CloudBand: deployment architecture</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"> <a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/SBC_pic.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-283\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/SBC_pic.jpg\" alt=\"SBC_pic\" width=\"940\" height=\"475\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\">\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Example: Operational benefits of cloud deployment</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"table-1\">\r\n<table width=\"100%\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th width=\"15%\">Attribute</th>\r\n<th>Conventional</th>\r\n<th>CloudBand</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Appliance</td>\r\n<td>Hardware appliance of software application on generic server (bare-metal) architected for peak capacity</td>\r\n<td>Virtualized software appliance on cloud infrastructure architected for current capacity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Deployment</td>\r\n<td>Site engineer investigates, deployment engineer installs, configures and provisions the system and monitors heath</td>\r\n<td>Management and orchestration system deploys new instance with standard configuration and automatically monitors health</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scale</td>\r\n<td>Add new cards/blades/servers into the system hardware and perform reconfiguration (re-architect with capacity planning)</td>\r\n<td>Orchestration system adds additional instances of the appliance and updates master-slave relationship configuration – can add/remove as many slaves as necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Upgrade</td>\r\n<td>Replace new upgraded blade with existing blade</td>\r\n<td>Upgrade a new virtual instance and simply switch traffic to it. Delete old instance</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Operations</td>\r\n<td>Hardware, operating system, application, alarms</td>\r\n<td>Operating system, hypervisor, application, alarms</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Multi-tenancy</td>\r\n<td>Service partitioning of hardware based systems can be quite cumbersome – or deploy multiple, parallel hardware/software systems</td>\r\n<td>Create a new service slice by deploying new application instance and service chain with other NFV components</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-SBC-v2.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\"  href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-Metaswitch-SBC-v1.pdf\">Powerpoint</a>", "VIRTUAL SBC", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "282-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 12:00:40", "2015-10-27 07:00:40", "", "282", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/282-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("965", "1", "2015-10-27 12:03:10", "2015-10-27 07:03:10", "<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Value to the ecosystem</h2>\r\n</div>\r\nA session border controller (SBC) is a network element used to support voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP), multimedia, next-generation presence-based applications for wireline, 3G and voice over LTE, IMS and pre-IMS networks.\r\n\r\nSBCs play an important role at the network edge by providing signaling and media security, service level agreement assurance and regulatory compliance capabilities. SBC features for multimedia applications such as voice, fax and video include: far- and near-end Network Address Translation traversal/firewall; secure Real-time Transport Protocol; IPv4/IPv6 networking; Call Admission Control; session routing; overload protection; transcoding; and quality of service and regulatory compliance.\r\n\r\nSBCs can be located at smaller points of presence – supporting as few as 5000 subscribers – or in larger central offices or data centers supporting millions of subscribers. It is a critical component for managing Internet traffic to help safeguard the multimedia communications that are integral to our daily lives as the number of IP devices continues to grow.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Key Benefits:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"list-icon circle-no list-icon-color-#000 list-icon-check\">\r\n	<li>SBC signaling functions are very compute intensive and will greatly benefit from implementation on commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) cloud infrastructure</li>\r\n	<li>An important SBC function is to protect against denial of service and distributed denial of services attacks – using low-cost hardware to manage unexpected surges while maintaining support for non-attack traffic is crucial.</li>\r\n	<li>Just-in-time deployment flexibility</li>\r\n	<li>Almost infinite elasticity and scalability</li>\r\n	<li>Support for new services, such as “SBC as a service”</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Solutions</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nThe SBC is well suited to cloud deployment, where it can be fully virtualized and deployed on a cloud Network Function Virtualization platform such as CloudBand. There it can take full advantage of the underlying infrastructure to obtain the necessary distributed or local deployment flexibility, elasticity, reliability and high availability. These are all critical for carrier-grade operations; however cloud deployment eliminates the need for closed, customized or proprietary hardware. The common, distributed infrastructure – with centralized management and orchestration – can be shared between many similar carrier-specific applications to achieve economies of scale.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Cloud-based Session Border Controller:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nThe virtualized SBC is deployed onto the CloudBand platform using the carrier platform as a service (cPaaS) layer by creating a set of recipes (like a template or a cookie cutter) that deploy the necessary service tiers for the application and manage the relationship between these services. In addition, the recipe provides full application lifecycle management, including scaling (based on defined key performance indicators), self-healing and upgrading. This essentially creates a simple, one-touch, automated, end-to-end application deployment that also accommodates any operator-specific constraints.\r\n\r\nDue to the cookie-cutter nature of the application template, deploying multiple instances requires little time or effort. Further, the underlying infrastructure, in conjunction with the management and orchestration system, provides the necessary reliability, availability and security for the application to meet the strict carrier-grade requirements, all on COTS hardware.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>SBC on CloudBand: deployment architecture</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"> <a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/SBC_pic.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-283\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/SBC_pic.jpg\" alt=\"SBC_pic\" width=\"940\" height=\"475\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\">\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Example: Operational benefits of cloud deployment</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"table-1\">\r\n<table width=\"100%\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th width=\"15%\">Attribute</th>\r\n<th>Conventional</th>\r\n<th>CloudBand</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Appliance</td>\r\n<td>Hardware appliance of software application on generic server (bare-metal) architected for peak capacity</td>\r\n<td>Virtualized software appliance on cloud infrastructure architected for current capacity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Deployment</td>\r\n<td>Site engineer investigates, deployment engineer installs, configures and provisions the system and monitors heath</td>\r\n<td>Management and orchestration system deploys new instance with standard configuration and automatically monitors health</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scale</td>\r\n<td>Add new cards/blades/servers into the system hardware and perform reconfiguration (re-architect with capacity planning)</td>\r\n<td>Orchestration system adds additional instances of the appliance and updates master-slave relationship configuration – can add/remove as many slaves as necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Upgrade</td>\r\n<td>Replace new upgraded blade with existing blade</td>\r\n<td>Upgrade a new virtual instance and simply switch traffic to it. Delete old instance</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Operations</td>\r\n<td>Hardware, operating system, application, alarms</td>\r\n<td>Operating system, hypervisor, application, alarms</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Multi-tenancy</td>\r\n<td>Service partitioning of hardware based systems can be quite cumbersome – or deploy multiple, parallel hardware/software systems</td>\r\n<td>Create a new service slice by deploying new application instance and service chain with other NFV components</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-SBC-v2.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\"  href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-Metaswitch-SBC-v1.pdf\">Powerpoint</a>", "VIRTUAL SBC", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "282-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 12:03:10", "2015-10-27 07:03:10", "", "282", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/282-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("966", "1", "2015-10-27 12:04:24", "2015-10-27 07:04:24", "Virtual firewall appliances play a critical role within the cloud infrastructure, mitigating security risks by implementing appropriate security controls for inter-virtual machine (VM) – or VM to physical and vice-versa – communication and providing the necessary isolation on an application, zone, domain or tenant basis.\r\n\r\nNetwork-based security services were traditionally implemented by strategically placing physical “middle-boxes” across data centers and assuming the underlying network fabric would remain relatively static. However, new cloud architectures contain virtualized infrastructure, making the end-points (VMs) and the network fabric dynamic and subject to rapid change due to some triggering event, such as a failed compute/storage resource causing an automated response from the orchestration layer. This has created issues with the traditional network security approach, ranging from inflexible physical topologies, to firewalls becoming chokepoints, to loss of VM traffic visibility within the host, to name a few.\r\n\r\nIn a virtualized environment, network service functions such as firewalls can be rapidly deployed when and where needed – independent of physical locations or boundaries – and stitched together with other virtual or physical network services (e.g., load-balancers) though the network functions virtualization concept of “service chaining”. This allows an agile, responsive and dynamic virtual environment to be created that scales based on events and configuration updates. It also ensures businesses can continue to monitor and enforce the same set of security controls and compliance requirements on the new virtual environment as they would with the traditional physical one.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Key Benefits:</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<ul class=\"list-icon circle-no list-icon-color-#000 list-icon-check\">\r\n	<li>Basic building block for any virtual network fabric in cloud infrastructure for securing applications – both externally (using VPNs) and internally (zone/app firewall)</li>\r\n	<li>Elasticity/scalability based on demand conditions and operator defined KPIs</li>\r\n	<li>Self-healing of the firewall instances for high reliability and availability</li>\r\n	<li>Complete visibility and security of the virtual environment</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Solutions</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewalls are one of the basic building blocks within cloud infrastructure, required for securing access to/from the virtual environment as well as the applications running within the environment. Deployed within the virtual environment network fabric , they enable access controls to be used between virtual machines and other points in the virtual and physical environment. They play a significant role at various security layers – e.g. tenant isolation and security in a shared, multi-tenant environment (e.g. using VPNs); between applications within a given tenant (Zone firewall); between VMs within a given application (application firewall) and so on. They are essential in creating multi-tier virtual network functions/applications within a host environment.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Virtual Firewall Integration with CloudBand</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nVirtual firewall is deployed within CloudBand as an application appliance instance that can be used by other applications to create security controls between VMs within the application or across applications. There are two ways of using this virtual network function within CloudBand – it can be deployed as a standalone network function within a virtual network that is stitched together to form some higher level application/service or it can be deployed as a fully integrated network function within the framework of an application – e.g. a multi-tier web application. Independent of the deployment option, all applications are built by initially creating the necessary service templates called “recipes” using CloudBand’s cPaaS layer. The recipes essentially create the necessary service tiers for the application and manage the relationships between them, including all the scaling rules, healing rules, upgrades etc. The recipe is used to onboard the application onto CloudBand and make it available within the application/service catalogue for deployment.\r\n\r\nThe service provider/user can deploy the application by simply selecting the application from the application catalogue menu and providing any additional application-specific and/or operations-specific (business policy constraints) deployment parameters required. Upon deployment, the cPaaS manager monitors and controls the application activity as per the recipe definition/service template and the business policy constraints provided. CloudBand and cPaaS automatically provide all the underlying platform benefits to all deployed applications – such as elasticity, scalability, performance, reliability, availability, security and other common carrier-grade features – all without the need of deploying the applications on customized, proprietary hardware. Further, due to the cookie-cutter nature of the application template, deploying multiple instances requires little time or effort. The end result is the overall reduction in total cost of ownership for any deployed application – both in terms of Capex (since COTS hardware is employed) as well as Opex.\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall on CloudBand use case: simple multi-tier application deployment architecture</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-278\" src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/use_case_FW_page_pic.jpg\" alt=\"use_case_FW_page_pic\" width=\"940\" height=\"475\" /></a>\r\n<div class=\"title\">\r\n<h2>Firewall Cloudification Benefits: Operational Aspects</h2>\r\n<div class=\"title-sep-container\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"table-1\">\r\n<table width=\"100%\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th width=\"15%\">Attribute</th>\r\n<th>Conventional</th>\r\n<th>CloudBand</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Appliance</td>\r\n<td>Hardware appliance of software application on generic server (bare-metal) architected for peak capacity</td>\r\n<td>Virtualized software appliance on cloud infrastructure architected for current capacity</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Deployment</td>\r\n<td>Site engineer investigates, deployment engineer installs, configures and provisions the system and monitors heath</td>\r\n<td>Management and orchestration system deploys new instance with standard configuration and automatically monitors health</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scale</td>\r\n<td>Add new cards/blades/servers into the system hardware and perform reconfiguration (re-architect with capacity planning)</td>\r\n<td>Orchestration system adds additional instances of the appliance and updates master-slave relationship configuration – can add/remove as many slaves as necessary</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Upgrade</td>\r\n<td>Replace new upgraded blade with existing blade</td>\r\n<td>Upgrade a new virtual instance and simply switch traffic to it. Delete old instance</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Operations</td>\r\n<td>Hardware, operating system, application, alarms</td>\r\n<td>Operating system, hypervisor, application, alarms</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Multi-tenancy</td>\r\n<td>Service partitioning of hardware based systems can be quite cumbersome – or deploy multiple, parallel hardware/software systems</td>\r\n<td>Create a new service slice by deploying new application instance and service chain with other NFV components</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href==\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v3.pdf\">Download full info on this use case</a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"protected\" href=\"#\" data-url=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/NFV-CB-FW-v2.pdf\">Powerpoint</a>", "VIRTUAL FIREWALL", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "273-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 12:04:24", "2015-10-27 07:04:24", "", "273", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/273-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("969", "5", "2015-10-27 19:29:12", "2015-10-27 14:29:12", "<div class=\"row featured-video\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-2\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-8\">\r\n<h2>Featured Video</h2>\r\n<iframe width=\"720\" height=\"504\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/6JWyITbT8ec?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3>NFV: moving from proof of concepts  to commercial deployment</h3>\r\nNFV acceptance  is progressing rapidly, with many proof of concepts and trials now completed,  the focus is definitely shifting towards commercial deployments.  A key success factor for NFV is the adoption of virtualization by Network Function Vendors who will play a key role in the transformation to NFV.  This video is the highlight of interviews with four major network function vendors who share their view on NFV and their strategy in moving towards virtualization.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-2\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/tTVeexoVU54?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Alcatel-Lucent provides operators with the oxygen to innovate</strong></h3>\r\nThe goal with the new technologies, NFV and SDN, is to increase operational efficiency - that gives operators the oxygen to innovate. All the functions Alcatel-Lucent already has live in the network are on a virtualisation and cloudification journey.  In this video, Bashkar Ghorti, highlights Alcatel-Lucent vision and strategy in enabling service provider to deploy NFV.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Nq9eeW_-SmM?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Using NFV to reach the services existing technology</strong></h3>\r\nPeter Margaris outlines the opportunities versus the challenges of NFV, as F5 sees them and, as a vendor of NFV equipment, explains how the virtualisation technology will particularly affect Layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model. He also lists the benefits of working in close collaboration with Alcatel-Lucent and just what Alcatel-Lucent\'s end-to-end and open NFV platform and ecosystem, CloudBand, brings to the party.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4 last\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/cA29TCfvd7Y?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Leveraging NFV to become a pure software vendor</strong></h3>\r\nProcera Networks is a vendor of NFV equipment and Cam Cullen, VP, Global Marketing,  explains the strategic underpinning of the industry shift from reliance on physical devices to full-blown Networks Functions Virtualisation. He also details the importance and benefits of working in close collaboration with Alcatel Lucent and the importance of its CloudBand NFV platform.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!--row-->\r\n<div class=\"clearboth\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/DMrd_xZmc0A?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Helping service providers change platforms: from transport to innovation</strong></h3>\r\nAlistair Scott, Director, CTO Office, JDSU explains that as the ripples caused by the global shift to cloud, network transformation and virtualisation continue to spread, companies are having to come to terms with a rapidly changing world - and that can be difficult. JDSU is also in long-term partnership with Alcatel-Lucent to provide world-beating virtualisation solutions for CSPs.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4 last\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ug2MtqJDF-M?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Enabling a network-wide cyber defence strategy with NFV</strong></h3>\r\nMichael O’Malley, VP Carrier Strategy & BD, outlines Radware\'s SDN and NFV strategy for mobile carriers and service providers and emphasises the importance of applying an integrated security and application delivery framework that seamlessly enables comprehensive cyber defence and service delivery as network-wide native services. He also talks about the importance of Radware\'s ongoing collaboration with Alcatel Lucent and the many benefits it brings to both parties\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4 last\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MfspeJrIqCI?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Lightreading exclusive interview with Basil Alwan, President IP Routing & Transport - Alcatel-Lucent</strong></h3>\r\nBasil Alwan, President of IP Routing & Transport at Alcatel-Lucent, discusses virtualization, cultural challenges, the capex crunch and more with Light Reading founder and CEO Steve Saunders\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-2\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Y6VCgMkgDr4?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Bringing NFV to production with CloudBand 3.0</strong></h3>\r\nRon Haberman, General Manager for Alcatel-Lucent  CloudBand business unit, talks about what CloudBand 3.0 means for the Service Provider.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-4\">\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"288\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/bgcNRBl0nVQ?showinfo=0\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<h3><strong>Innovation and Lean Operations</strong></h3>\r\nThis interactive demonstration by the Cloud Innovation Center (CIC) shows the positive impact of agile service launch subject to Reliability, Availability, Serviceability (RAS) scenarios. It features an application centered system involving sophisticated Virtual Network Functions (VNF) and integrates Operations Support System (OSS), NFV’s Management and Orchestration (MANO) as well as Software Defined Networking (SDN) under a modular and scalable approach. In addition to Alcatel-Lucent’s portfolio, our conversation illustrates Ecosystem examples involving third party partners.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!--row-->", "Videos", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "516-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-10-27 19:29:12", "2015-10-27 14:29:12", "", "516", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/516-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("996", "5", "2015-11-06 20:51:29", "2015-11-06 15:51:29", "<em>Taking a break from my ongoing “Transformation for NFV” blog series in order to recount some of my thoughts from October’s SDN & Openflow World Congress. \r\n\r\nNext week we’re back to the series with some insights on where to start if you’re a Service Provider looking to transform your operations to NFV.</em>\r\n\r\nAround March this year I described my experiences during Mobile World Congress in Barcelona. One of the things I talked about that was extremely evident was the feeling of excitement around NFV, the promise it brings and the fact that so many operators were starting to talk about real deployments and really getting out of the POC phase.\r\n\r\nSo the conversation at MWC was mostly about the changing paradigm, about going to the next level and making NFV happen.\r\n\r\nNow, only about six months later, it’s a completely different story (and in a good way)!\r\n\r\nNFV has definitely moved past the hype stage, and settled firmly into its place as the only way to really make a difference in cost reduction and operational efficiency. So yes – maybe some of the glamour is fading, and it’s not all shiny and new. But here’s the good news – we can finally relax and cut out all the bling and really get down to work on widespread global deployment that will truly benefit operators (and not just Tier 1 types).\r\n\r\nAnd SDN & Openflow World Congress was a prime example of how a Telco technology adoption lifecycle works. Many of the keynotes I listened to talked about where NFV is after 3 years, and the conclusions were optimistic but also extremely down to earth and pragmatic.\r\n\r\nFor example, Axel Clauberg of Deutsche Telekom showed this timeline. Coming from one of the largest service providers in the world I think it’s a pretty confident point of view:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1-300x183.jpg\" alt=\"1\" width=\"300\" height=\"183\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-984\" /></a>\r\nsource: Deutsche Telekom, 2015\r\n\r\nIn their keynote, another global service provider you may have heard of – Orange, talked about their pragmatic approach to network agility. And provided this reassuring statement:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/2.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/2-300x44.jpg\" alt=\"2\" width=\"300\" height=\"44\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-986\" /></a>\r\nsource: Orange, 2015\r\n\r\nAnd Cable labs provided an overview of the extent to which NFV & SDN have become commonplace in the market:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/3.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/3-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"3\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-987\" /></a>\r\nsource: CableLabs, 2015\r\n\r\nMuch of the conversation, again taking this pragmatic approach revolved around relevant use cases going into production in the current timeline:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/4.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/4-300x224.jpg\" alt=\"4\" width=\"300\" height=\"224\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-988\" /></a> \r\nsource: Infonetics, 2015\r\n\r\nAnd operationalizing NFV use cases is also top of mind at CloudBand, which is why we held several focused workshops around service availability and performance as well as the CloudBand ecosystem, openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nRepresentatives from some of our leading ecosystem members such as F5, Palo Alto Networks and NFWare shared their vision for interoperability and their experience working with our orchestration platform during the Ecosystem workshop. It was especially important for us here to show how crucial it is to have a rich and diverse ecosystem of app vendors contributing to MANO openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nIn another Alcatel-Lucent workshop we delved into some of the challenges faced by our customers who are deploying NFV and actually had the privilege to hear these customers, including Rostelecom and NTT describe their experiences.\r\n \r\nAnd a great deal of the agenda (including our own) was also dedicated to discussing open-source in general, the various open source initiatives around NFV and specifically the need for open source to take center stage as the growth engine for NFV.\r\n\r\nI’m really pleased to say that we’ve been taking a good hard look at our open source efforts and have been making the necessary adjustments to our open source strategies as a result of the intensive involvement we have with our customers. In my presentation during the Alcatel-Lucent workshop I discussed the market’s expectations from open source:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"5\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-989\" /></a>\r\nand how we’re addressing these expectations:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"6\" width=\"300\" height=\"226\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-990\" /></a>\r\n\r\nContinuing this line of thought, Ron Haberman, CloudBand’s GM gave a keynote that continued the theme we started in 2014, in which we described our own personal transformation as a vendor. Whereas last year we talked about the changes we undertook for NFV in general, this year we illustrated our transformation the most relevant of topics – open source.\r\n\r\nIt’s a humbling experience as a vendor to talk about the oversights you made and the realization that you need to change in order to adapt to market needs, but an honest recounting of these insights is fascinating and provides our customers with the understanding that we are looking out for their best interests.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"7\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-991\" /></a> \r\n\r\nNow CloudBand’s been a staunch supporter of open source since the day of inception. So open source is not new to us, but we’ve stepped things up and are now actively writing upstream code, becoming heavily involved with the community and really embracing all aspects of open-source.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"8\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-992\" /></a> \r\n\r\nAnd I’m especially proud that at SDN & Openflow World Congress we also launched our very own open source initiative – Vitrage – an OpenStack root cause analysis (RCA) engine project. Vitrage’s goal is to develop an engine for organizing, analyzing and expanding OpenStack alarms & events, generating insights on the Root Cause of problems and deducing the existence of problems before they’re detected.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\" alt=\"9\" width=\"293\" height=\"220\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-993\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe’re really excited about this project and truly believe it can gain real traction in the OpenStack community. We’re already beginning to see the enthusiasm from the community following the Openstack summit last week, so stay tuned for more news about Vitrage – it’s going to be a thrilling ride!\r\n\r\nIn the meantime, you can learn more about Vitrage here:\r\nhttps://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Vitrage\r\n\r\nUntil next time, \r\nGuy\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n", "SDN & Openflow World Congress - Event Recap", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "983-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-11-06 20:51:29", "2015-11-06 15:51:29", "", "983", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/983-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
