h and diverse ecosystem of app vendors contributing to MANO openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nIn another Alcatel-Lucent workshop we delved into some of the challenges faced by our customers who are deploying NFV and actually had the privilege to hear these customers, including Rostelecom and NTT describe their experiences.\r\n \r\nAnd a great deal of the agenda (including our own) was also dedicated to discussing open-source in general, the various open source initiatives around NFV and specifically the need for open source to take center stage as the growth engine for NFV.\r\n\r\nI’m really pleased to say that we’ve been taking a good hard look at our open source efforts and have been making the necessary adjustments to our open source strategies as a result of the intensive involvement we have with our customers. In my presentation during the Alcatel-Lucent workshop I discussed the market’s expectations from open source:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"5\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-989\" /></a>\r\nand how we’re addressing these expectations:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"6\" width=\"300\" height=\"226\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-990\" /></a>\r\n\r\nContinuing this line of thought, Ron Haberman, CloudBand’s GM gave a keynote that continued the theme we started in 2014, in which we described our own personal transformation as a vendor. Whereas last year we talked about the changes we undertook for NFV in general, this year we illustrated our transformation the most relevant of topics – open source.\r\n\r\nIt’s a humbling experience as a vendor to talk about the oversights you made and the realization that you need to change in order to adapt to market needs, but an honest recounting of these insights is fascinating and provides our customers with the understanding that we are looking out for their best interests.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"7\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-991\" /></a> \r\n\r\nNow CloudBand’s been a staunch supporter of open source since the day of inception. So open source is not new to us, but we’ve stepped things up and are now actively writing upstream code, becoming heavily involved with the community and really embracing all aspects of open-source.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"8\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-992\" /></a> \r\n\r\nAnd I’m especially proud that at SDN & Openflow World Congress we also launched our very own open source initiative – Vitrage – an OpenStack root cause analysis (RCA) engine project. Vitrage’s goal is to develop an engine for organizing, analyzing and expanding OpenStack alarms & events, generating insights on the Root Cause of problems and deducing the existence of problems before they’re detected.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\" alt=\"9\" width=\"293\" height=\"220\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-993\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe’re really excited about this project and truly believe it can gain real traction in the OpenStack community. We’re already beginning to see the enthusiasm from the community following the Openstack summit last week, so stay tuned for more news about Vitrage – it’s going to be a thrilling ride!\r\n\r\nIn the meantime, you can learn more about Vitrage here:\r\nhttps://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Vitrage\r\n\r\nUntil next time, \r\nGuy\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n", "SDN & Openflow Word Congress - Event Recap", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "983-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-11-04 19:37:35", "2015-11-04 14:37:35", "", "983", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/983-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("995", "5", "2015-11-04 19:39:16", "2015-11-04 14:39:16", "<em>Taking a break from my ongoing “Transformation for NFV” blog series in order to recount some of my thoughts from October’s SDN & Openflow World Congress. \r\n\r\nNext week we’re back to the series with some insights on where to start if you’re a Service Provider looking to transform your operations to NFV.</em>\r\n\r\nAround March this year I described my experiences during Mobile World Congress in Barcelona. One of the things I talked about that was extremely evident was the feeling of excitement around NFV, the promise it brings and the fact that so many operators were starting to talk about real deployments and really getting out of the POC phase.\r\n\r\nSo the conversation at MWC was mostly about the changing paradigm, about going to the next level and making NFV happen.\r\n\r\nNow, only about six months later, it’s a completely different story (and in a good way)!\r\n\r\nNFV has definitely moved past the hype stage, and settled firmly into its place as the only way to really make a difference in cost reduction and operational efficiency. So yes – maybe some of the glamour is fading, and it’s not all shiny and new. But here’s the good news – we can finally relax and cut out all the bling and really get down to work on widespread global deployment that will truly benefit operators (and not just Tier 1 types).\r\n\r\nAnd SDN & Openflow World Congress was a prime example of how a Telco technology adoption lifecycle works. Many of the keynotes I listened to talked about where NFV is after 3 years, and the conclusions were optimistic but also extremely down to earth and pragmatic.\r\n\r\nFor example, Axel Clauberg of Deutsche Telekom showed this timeline. Coming from one of the largest service providers in the world I think it’s a pretty confident point of view:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1-300x183.jpg\" alt=\"1\" width=\"300\" height=\"183\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-984\" /></a>\r\nsource: Deutsche Telekom, 2015\r\n\r\nIn their keynote, another global service provider you may have heard of – Orange, talked about their pragmatic approach to network agility. And provided this reassuring statement:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/2.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/2-300x44.jpg\" alt=\"2\" width=\"300\" height=\"44\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-986\" /></a>\r\nsource: Orange, 2015\r\n\r\nAnd Cable labs provided an overview of the extent to which NFV & SDN have become commonplace in the market:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/3.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/3-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"3\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-987\" /></a>\r\nsource: CableLabs, 2015\r\n\r\nMuch of the conversation, again taking this pragmatic approach revolved around relevant use cases going into production in the current timeline:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/4.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/4-300x224.jpg\" alt=\"4\" width=\"300\" height=\"224\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-988\" /></a> \r\nsource: Infonetics, 2015\r\n\r\nAnd operationalizing NFV use cases is also top of mind at CloudBand, which is why we held several focused workshops around service availability and performance as well as the CloudBand ecosystem, openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nRepresentatives from some of our leading ecosystem members such as F5, Palo Alto Networks and NFWare shared their vision for interoperability and their experience working with our orchestration platform during the Ecosystem workshop. It was especially important for us here to show how crucial it is to have a rich and diverse ecosystem of app vendors contributing to MANO openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nIn another Alcatel-Lucent workshop we delved into some of the challenges faced by our customers who are deploying NFV and actually had the privilege to hear these customers, including Rostelecom and NTT describe their experiences.\r\n \r\nAnd a great deal of the agenda (including our own) was also dedicated to discussing open-source in general, the various open source initiatives around NFV and specifically the need for open source to take center stage as the growth engine for NFV.\r\n\r\nI’m really pleased to say that we’ve been taking a good hard look at our open source efforts and have been making the necessary adjustments to our open source strategies as a result of the intensive involvement we have with our customers. In my presentation during the Alcatel-Lucent workshop I discussed the market’s expectations from open source:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"5\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-989\" /></a>\r\nand how we’re addressing these expectations:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"6\" width=\"300\" height=\"226\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-990\" /></a>\r\n\r\nContinuing this line of thought, Ron Haberman, CloudBand’s GM gave a keynote that continued the theme we started in 2014, in which we described our own personal transformation as a vendor. Whereas last year we talked about the changes we undertook for NFV in general, this year we illustrated our transformation the most relevant of topics – open source.\r\n\r\nIt’s a humbling experience as a vendor to talk about the oversights you made and the realization that you need to change in order to adapt to market needs, but an honest recounting of these insights is fascinating and provides our customers with the understanding that we are looking out for their best interests.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"7\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-991\" /></a> \r\n\r\nNow CloudBand’s been a staunch supporter of open source since the day of inception. So open source is not new to us, but we’ve stepped things up and are now actively writing upstream code, becoming heavily involved with the community and really embracing all aspects of open-source.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"8\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-992\" /></a> \r\n\r\nAnd I’m especially proud that at SDN & Openflow World Congress we also launched our very own open source initiative – Vitrage – an OpenStack root cause analysis (RCA) engine project. Vitrage’s goal is to develop an engine for organizing, analyzing and expanding OpenStack alarms & events, generating insights on the Root Cause of problems and deducing the existence of problems before they’re detected.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\" alt=\"9\" width=\"293\" height=\"220\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-993\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe’re really excited about this project and truly believe it can gain real traction in the OpenStack community. We’re already beginning to see the enthusiasm from the community following the Openstack summit last week, so stay tuned for more news about Vitrage – it’s going to be a thrilling ride!\r\n\r\nIn the meantime, you can learn more about Vitrage here:\r\nhttps://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Vitrage\r\n\r\nUntil next time, \r\nGuy\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n", "SDN & Openflow Word Congress - Event Recap", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "983-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-11-04 19:39:16", "2015-11-04 14:39:16", "", "983", "http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/983-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
