w how crucial it is to have a rich and diverse ecosystem of app vendors contributing to MANO openness and interoperability.\r\n\r\nIn another Alcatel-Lucent workshop we delved into some of the challenges faced by our customers who are deploying NFV and actually had the privilege to hear these customers, including Rostelecom and NTT describe their experiences.\r\n \r\nAnd a great deal of the agenda (including our own) was also dedicated to discussing open-source in general, the various open source initiatives around NFV and specifically the need for open source to take center stage as the growth engine for NFV.\r\n\r\nI’m really pleased to say that we’ve been taking a good hard look at our open source efforts and have been making the necessary adjustments to our open source strategies as a result of the intensive involvement we have with our customers. In my presentation during the Alcatel-Lucent workshop I discussed the market’s expectations from open source:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/5-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"5\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-989\" /></a>\r\nand how we’re addressing these expectations:\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/6-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"6\" width=\"300\" height=\"226\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-990\" /></a>\r\n\r\nContinuing this line of thought, Ron Haberman, CloudBand’s GM gave a keynote that continued the theme we started in 2014, in which we described our own personal transformation as a vendor. Whereas last year we talked about the changes we undertook for NFV in general, this year we illustrated our transformation the most relevant of topics – open source.\r\n\r\nIt’s a humbling experience as a vendor to talk about the oversights you made and the realization that you need to change in order to adapt to market needs, but an honest recounting of these insights is fascinating and provides our customers with the understanding that we are looking out for their best interests.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/7-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"7\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-991\" /></a> \r\n\r\nNow CloudBand’s been a staunch supporter of open source since the day of inception. So open source is not new to us, but we’ve stepped things up and are now actively writing upstream code, becoming heavily involved with the community and really embracing all aspects of open-source.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/8-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"8\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-992\" /></a> \r\n\r\nAnd I’m especially proud that at SDN & Openflow World Congress we also launched our very own open source initiative – Vitrage – an OpenStack root cause analysis (RCA) engine project. Vitrage’s goal is to develop an engine for organizing, analyzing and expanding OpenStack alarms & events, generating insights on the Root Cause of problems and deducing the existence of problems before they’re detected.\r\n<a href=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\"><img src=\"http://ecosystem.cloud-band.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/9.jpg\" alt=\"9\" width=\"293\" height=\"220\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-993\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe’re really excited about this project and truly believe it can gain real traction in the OpenStack community. We’re already beginning to see the enthusiasm from the community following the Openstack summit last week, so stay tuned for more news about Vitrage – it’s going to be a thrilling ride!\r\n\r\nIn the